{"award_age":71.0,"bio_image":"full\/479d74e799e8eeedee34e7d8e716656b4eac18e4.jpg","category":"Economics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1939-02-02T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2014-01-09T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/5\/55\/Dale_Mortensen_2.jpg\/220px-Dale_Mortensen_2.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen","mini_bio":"<p><b>Dale Thomas Mortensen<\/b> (February 2, 1939 \u2013 January 9, 2014) was an American economist. He received his B.A. in economics from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willamette_University\" title=\"Willamette University\">Willamette University<\/a> and his PhD in Economics from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Carnegie_Mellon_University\" title=\"Carnegie Mellon University\">Carnegie Mellon University<\/a>. Born in Enterprise, Oregon,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> he was a member of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Beta_Theta_Pi\" title=\"Beta Theta Pi\">Beta Theta Pi<\/a> fraternity. He had been on the faculty of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Northwestern_University\" title=\"Northwestern University\">Northwestern University<\/a> since 1965 and a professor of Managerial Economics and Decision Sciences at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Kellogg_School_of_Management\" title=\"Kellogg School of Management\">Kellogg School of Management<\/a> since 1980.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was the Niels Bohr Visiting Professor at the School of Economics and Management, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Aarhus_University\" title=\"Aarhus University\">Aarhus University<\/a>, from 2006 to 2010.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Economics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Economics\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize in Economics<\/a> jointly with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Christopher_A._Pissarides\" title=\"Christopher A. Pissarides\">Christopher A. Pissarides<\/a> from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/London_School_of_Economics\" title=\"London School of Economics\">London School of Economics<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Peter_A._Diamond\" title=\"Peter A. Diamond\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Peter A. Diamond<\/a> from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology\" title=\"Massachusetts Institute of Technology\">Massachusetts Institute of Technology<\/a> in 2010 \"for their analysis of markets with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Search_theory\" title=\"Search theory\">search<\/a> frictions\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-nobel-2010_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen#cite_note-nobel-2010-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In May 2011, Mortensen was awarded an honorary Doctor of Science degree from his alma mater, Willamette University.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen#cite_note-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was married to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Beverly_Mortensen\" title=\"Beverly Mortensen\">Beverly Mortensen<\/a>, also a Northwestern Professor.<\/p><p>Mortensen's research focused on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Labour_economics\" title=\"Labour economics\">labor economics<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Macroeconomics\" title=\"Macroeconomics\">macroeconomics<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Economic_theory\" title=\"Economic theory\" class=\"mw-redirect\">economic theory<\/a>. He is especially known for his pioneering work on the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Search_and_matching_theory\" title=\"Search and matching theory\" class=\"mw-redirect\">search and matching theory<\/a> of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Unemployment_types#Frictional_unemployment\" title=\"Unemployment types\" class=\"mw-redirect\">frictional unemployment<\/a>. He extended the insights from this work to study labor turnover and reallocation, research and development, and personal relationships.<\/p><p>Mortensen was a past president of the Society of Economic Dynamics and one of the founding editors of the Review of Economic Dynamics.<\/p><p>Mortensen died of cancer on January 9, 2014 at the age of 74, at his home in Wilmette.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen#cite_note-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen#cite_note-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen#cite_note-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dale_T._Mortensen#cite_note-9\"><span>[<\/span>9<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Dale T. Mortensen","place_of_birth":"Enterprise, Oregon, USA","place_of_death":"Wilmette, Illinois","text":"Dale T. Mortensen , Economics, 2010","year":2010.0}